        </ol>
      </nav>

      <h2 id="quick-pick">⚡ Quick Pick: What Should I Use?</h2>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Your Trip</th><th>Best Option</th><th>Why</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>3–7 day trip, 1–2 cities</td><td><strong>eSIM</strong></td><td>Zero setup hassle. Works on landing. No Chinese number needed.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>10+ day trip, multiple cities</td><td><strong>eSIM + VPN combo</strong></td><td>eSIM for data, VPN for laptop/long sessions.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Living/working in China</td><td><strong>Local SIM + VPN</strong></td><td>You need a Chinese number for Didi, food delivery, etc.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Just need Google Maps + WhatsApp</td><td><strong>eSIM</strong></td><td>eSIM data bypasses the firewall entirely. Everything just works.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2 id="esim">📱 Option 1: eSIM — The Easy Button</h2>

      <p>An eSIM is a digital SIM card you install before leaving home. When you land in China, it connects to a local network (usually China Unicom) but routes your data through Hong Kong or Singapore — <strong>completely bypassing the Great Firewall</strong>. Google, Instagram, WhatsApp — everything works as if you're not in China at all.</p>

      <h3>Pros</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>✅ No VPN needed — all apps work normally</li>
        <li>✅ Install in 2 minutes before your flight</li>
        <li>✅ Data activates on landing automatically</li>
        <li>✅ No Chinese phone number required for setup</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Cons</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>❌ No Chinese phone number (can't use Didi, Meituan, etc.)</li>
        <li>❌ Data-only — no voice calls or SMS</li>
        <li>❌ More expensive per GB than local SIMs</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Recommended eSIM Providers</h3>

      <p><strong><a href="https://airalo.tp.st/4w5I5IQK" rel="nofollow sponsored">Airalo</a></strong> — Our top pick. China plans start at $5 for 1 GB (7 days). The "Chinacom" eSIM connects through Hong Kong, completely bypassing censorship. Install via their app, activate on landing. 4.5/5 rating across 10,000+ reviews.</p>

      <p><strong><a href="https://saily.com" rel="nofollow sponsored">Saily</a></strong> — Good alternative from the NordVPN team. Similar pricing, slightly better speeds in some regions. Plans from $9 for 1 GB.</p>

      <p><strong>Both work.</strong> Airalo has better coverage for multi-country Asia trips. Saily is a bit cheaper for China-only plans.</p>

      <h2 id="vpn">🔐 Option 2: VPN — The Power User Option</h2>

      <p>A VPN encrypts your internet traffic and routes it through a server outside China, making blocked sites accessible. This is the traditional approach and still works — <strong>if you pick the right VPN</strong>.</p>

      <div style="background:#fff3cd;border-left:4px solid #ffc107;padding:1rem 1.25rem;margin:1.5rem 0;border-radius:0 8px 8px 0">
        <strong>⚠️ Critical:</strong> Install and test your VPN <strong>before</strong> you leave home. Once you're in China, VPN websites are blocked — you cannot download or purchase a VPN after arrival.
      </div>

      <h3>VPNs We've Tested & That Work in China</h3>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>VPN</th><th>Works in China?</th><th>Price</th><th>Best For</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
