            <td>$7.99/mo</td>
            <td>Chinese-made VPN optimized for the firewall. Simple, but less privacy.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>We Recommend</h3>
      <p>For most travelers: <strong>365VPN</strong> is the sweet spot — cheap, reliable, and built specifically for China. For privacy-conscious users: <strong>ProtonVPN</strong> with Stealth protocol.</p>

      <h2 id="localsim">📲 Option 3: Local SIM + VPN Combo</h2>

      <p>If you're staying more than 2 weeks, get a Chinese SIM card. You <em>need</em> a Chinese phone number for:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Didi (ride-hailing — app requires SMS verification)</li>
        <li>Meituan (food delivery)</li>
        <li>Restaurant queuing systems (they text you when your table is ready)</li>
        <li>Some WiFi networks (especially airports)</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>Where to get one:</strong> China Unicom booth at the airport (arrivals hall). Bring your passport. Tourist SIMs: ~$30 for 7 days, ~$50 for 30 days. You'll get a Chinese number + data, but the data is still behind the firewall — so you'll need a VPN too.</p>

      <h2 id="banned">🚫 VPNs That Don't Work in China</h2>

      <p>Not all VPNs are created equal. Here are popular VPNs that <strong>reliably fail</strong> inside China:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>❌ NordVPN — Blocked since 2022</li>
        <li>❌ ExpressVPN — Spotty at best</li>
        <li>❌ Surfshark — Doesn't connect</li>
        <li>❌ CyberGhost — Blocked</li>
        <li>❌ PIA (Private Internet Access) — Blocked</li>
        <li>❌ Most free VPNs — Either blocked or sell your data</li>
      </ul>

      <div style="background:#d4edda;border-left:4px solid #28a745;padding:1rem 1.25rem;margin:1.5rem 0;border-radius:0 8px 8px 0">
        <strong>💡 The honest strategy:</strong> We list every VPN that reliably works in China, and we only earn a commission when you buy through our links for some of them. If a VPN isn't on our "works" list, it's because we tested it and it failed — not because we don't have an affiliate deal. Your connectivity matters more than our commission.
      </div>

      <h2 id="setup">✅ Pre-Flight Checklist</h2>

      <ol>
        <li><strong>Install your VPN or eSIM app</strong> before leaving home</li>
        <li><strong>Test your VPN</strong> — connect to a server and open Google</li>
        <li><strong>Download offline maps</strong> (Maps.me or Organic Maps) for your cities</li>
        <li><strong>Set up Alipay</strong> with your foreign credit card — <a href="/guides/general/first-time-china-survival#payments">step-by-step Alipay guide →</a></li>
        <li><strong>Save offline translations</strong> (Google Translate offline pack for Chinese)</li>
        <li><strong>Screenshot</strong> your hotel address in Chinese (for taxi drivers)</li>
        <li><strong>Write down important numbers</strong> — in case your phone dies</li>
      </ol>

      <h2 id="faq">❓ FAQ</h2>

      <h3>Is it legal to use a VPN in China?</h3>
      <p>Using a VPN for personal use is a gray area. Millions of Chinese citizens and expats use VPNs daily without issue. Using a VPN to conduct illegal activities is, obviously, illegal. As a tourist using a VPN to check Gmail and Instagram, you will not face any problems.</p>

      <h3>Do eSIMs really bypass the firewall?</h3>
      <p>Yes. eSIMs from providers like Airalo route your data through servers outside China (typically Hong Kong or Singapore). From China's perspective, your data traffic looks like it's originating from outside the country. All apps work normally.</p>

      <h3>Can I buy a VPN after I arrive in China?</h3>
      <p>Generally no. VPN websites are blocked inside China. You need to purchase and install before departure. Some people have success using their eSIM data to download a VPN after arrival, but don't count on it.</p>

      <h3>Do I need a VPN if I have an eSIM?</h3>
      <p>No. An eSIM is sufficient by itself for staying connected. However, a VPN is useful as a backup (eSIM data can run out) and for connecting on WiFi networks.</p>

      <hr />

